courses.course_syllabus:
The topics will include:

- introduction to materials and tools;
- exercise of techniques in brushwork, tone variation and colouring;
- knowledge of Chinese painting such as mounting, inscriptions writing, seals stamping; and

- studies of four gentlemen, vegetable, figure, pine tree and rock.

courses.learning_outcomes:
After completing the course, students will be able to:

1. perceive diverse artistic potentials of form and space in daily surroundings;

2. develop ideas and concepts for 3D artistic expression;

3. understand and apply fundamental 3D elements and principles such as form-space-transformation, plane and volume, balance and gravity, scale and proportion, materials and textures etc…; and

4. manage wide range of tools and machinery for 3D construction both in handicraft and digital forming environment.

After taking this course, students are expected to get a basic understanding of:

1. The origin and development of major artistic traditions in China;

2. The artistic and cultural significance of Chinese art;

3. The achievements and contributions of great masters;

4. The ways of looking at Chinese art; and

5. The relationship between Chinese art and foreign culture.

courses.course_syllabus:
1. The art and culture of prehistoric and Bronze Age China;

2. Chinese ceramics and other decorative arts;

3. Chinese imperial art throughout the ages;

4. Art of the Chinese literati;

5. Chinese religious art; and

6. Artistic exchange between China and its neighboring countries.

courses.learning_outcomes:
After completing the course, students will be able to:

1. describe, discuss, and analyze works of art;
2. identify the relationship between the arts and the humanities;
3. understand the origin and development of major artistic traditions in China and beyond; and
4. conduct academic research on artwork and examine visual evidence critically

After completing the course, students will be able to:

- possess a broad understanding and appreciation of the multifarious artistic achievements of ancient China;
- acquaint with the "masterpieces" of ancient Chinese art from both recent archaeological excavations and in international museum collections;
- gain an awareness and knowledge of their cultural, technical, historical, and artistic characteristics, especially in regard to the major archaeological discoveries made in China over the past decades; and

- be prepared to pursue in greater depth each of the different art forms in more advanced courses or seminars.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

- understand the history of the silk road from the second century BC to the Song period;
- recognize the characteristics and significance of important artworks found along the silk road;
- acquire a balanced and updated understanding of the role played by cultural interaction in China's artistic development during the period concerned; and

- develop skills in writing academic essays.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

- understand the development of Chinese ceramics from the Neolithic period to the Song dynasty;
- analyse the visual characteristics of Chinese ceramics and their related ceramic technology;
- distinguish different types of archaeological sites and recognize the social and cultural significance of their ceramic finds; and

- develop skills in writing academic paper on Chinese ceramics.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

- understand the formation and development of the classical traditions of Chinese calligraphy;
- analyze the visual features as well as the aesthetic, social and cultural significance of classical Chinese calligraphy;
- evaluate critically the validity of different arguments concerning a work of Chinese calligraphy; and

- write academic papers on Chinese calligraphy

After completing the course, students will be able to:

- understand the development of visual and material cultures of the Ming dynasty

- explain the production technologies and visual characteristics of representative artworks and artefacts of the Ming dynasty;

- analyze different factors contributing to a social phenomenon related to images and objects in China;

- analyze and evaluate evidence and argument of academic papers;

- apply course knowledge and research methods to compose an academic essay.

After completing this course, students will be able to

- comprehend the basic academic framework and methodology of religious art;

- understand the roles, function and characteristics of religious art of China;

- analyse visual features of different art forms and their relation to religious beliefs and concepts;

- critically evaluate the validity of different arguments concerning a work of religious art;

- recognise religious ideas and appreciate artworks still prevail in Hong Kong nowadays, and trace their origins and development;

- develop skills in writing essays on history of Chinese art.

After completing this course, students will be able to:

1. Acquire rigorous art-historical methods in describing and analysing artistic monuments;
2. Identify major artistic traditions in pre-modern Asia and their inter-relations;
3. Think critically about works of art as integral part of a larger visual and material culture;
4. Explores the ways in which we construct knowledge on traditional Asian culture and society, especially, on the basis of unique modern experience of our era; and
5. Develop skills in participating in scholarly arguments and writing an academic essay.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

1. Know the development and changing status of comics and graphic novels within the wider history of Western Europe and North America;
2. identify how these changes took place and how they redefined comics and graphic novels in the present;
3. recognize the main artists of the medium, how they were influenced by their cultural context and how they also influenced it in return;
4. build informed opinion on the quality and relevance of the comics of the 20th and 21st century.
5. Develop skills in writing academic essays and speaking in public.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

- know the general timeframe of the developments of art in Hong Kong from the late 19th century to the present days;
- realize the uniqueness of Hong Kong culture (and other local cultures);
- think and write more precisely about the artworks made by Hong Kong artists in the territory or abroad; and

- recognize some of the most famous artworks produced by Hong Kong artists during that period.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

1. Understand the history of mineral-pigment painting and appreciate the unique beauty of classical Chinese murals;
2. Understand the development of mineral-pigment painting to the present;
3. Understand and master the materials and tools required for mineral-pigment painting;
4. Master the steps and techniques required for mineral-pigment painting;
5. Be aware of the uniqueness and limitations of mineral pigments;
6. Experiment, reconstruct or replace elements of mineral pigment painting and technical process; and
7. Independently complete mineral-pigment paintings and express personal ideas.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

- understand basics of camera and photographic paper;
- understand the differences of the analogue and digital format of photographic imaging;
- experiment and explore with alternative techniques through darkroom facilities; and

- understand different approaches and esthetics of photography.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

1. Understand fundamental oil or acrylic painting medium and its usage;
2. Understand basic 'language of painting';
3. Understand styles and artistic approaches of different periods in Western Art History, such as classical period, modern and postmodernism through various exercises; and

4. Develop ability of evaluation through class critique.

courses.course_syllabus:
1. Understand material and technique of oil painting;
2. Understand the concepts, approaches and techniques of classical period, impressionism, abstraction, and postmodernism;
3. Practice the above topics through student's own interpretation;
4. Learn the criteria of art appreciation and evaluation.

courses.learning_outcomes:
After completing the course, students will be able to:

1. Identify the seminal theoretical text related to archival practices in contemporary art;

2. Reflect on and develop artistic strategies in relation to archiving by understanding critical archival art practices;

3. Demonstrate the understanding of algorithm thinking through the basic use of data analytical tools;

4. Demonstrate an understanding of the basic use of digital preservation application;

5. Demonstrate an understanding of virtual technologies through the basic use of both software and hardware applications; and

6. Reflect on how contemporary art concept, data analytics, and technology intersect by creating an immersive narrative work.

After completing the course, students will:

- have knowledge of the origins and development of China’s ancient jade traditions from the Neolithic period through the early centuries of the Christian era (ca. 4000 BCE – 200 CE);
- have learned about major jade artifacts from excavated contexts as well as important collections both in China and the West;
- appreciate the technical, ritual, spiritual, cultural, historical, and artistic background that made jade a central icon of Chinese culture over millennia; and

- be prepared to pursue in greater depth (including graduation-level independent thesis research) some of the more complex artistic and spiritual issues related to the meaning of jade in China, and the role played by materials in defining the cultural character of early civilizations in general.

After completing the course, student will be able to:

- understand the historical development and technological achievements of Chinese ceramics from the Yuan to the Qing dynasty;
- analyze visual characteristics of Chinese ceramics in relation to their relevant ceramic technology and historical contexts of production and consumption;
- make use of different research materials and methodologies in conducting research; and

- write academic essays on Chinese ceramics.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

- understand the development of the Chinese calligraphy since the Song Dynasty;
- analyze the visual features as well as the aesthetic, social and cultural significance of Chinese calligraphy, particularly that produced by the literati and imperial members;
- evaluate critically the validity of different arguments concerning a work of Chinese calligraphy; and

- write academic papers on Chinese calligraphy

After completing the course, student will:

- have a firm grasp of the “masterpieces” of ancient China’s bronze-casting tradition from the 2nd millennium B.C. to the beginning of the Christian era, from both archaeological excavations and museum collections worldwide;
- understand the special characteristics of bronze-casting techniques in ancient China and how it developed to meet different needs of the society – as props for state and religious rituals, as functional weapons for battle, as luxury status symbols for the elite etc. ;
- appreciate the unique qualities of ancient China’s bronze-casting technology as a reflection not only of artistic sensibilities, but also as reflections of political, social, religious, and economic developments of the time; and

- be prepared to pursue in-depth (including graduation-level independent thesis research) some of the key issues related to metal technologies and their artistic, cultural, and economic role in ancient China and/or early societies in general

By completing the course, the students will:

1. Gain proficiency in analyzing an individual work of painting, sculpture, architecture, ceramic, and other high-end craft;
2. Comprehend overall geography and political history of Korea;
3. Reconsider the construct of “Korean” identity in its pre-modern, colonial, and post-colonial discourses;
4. Be enabled to think critically the process of Sinicization (i.e. the repercussions of Chinese culture in local context); and
5. Develop skills in participating in scholarly arguments and writing an academic essay.

By completing the course, the students will:

1. Gain proficiency in analyzing individual works of painting, sculpture, architecture, ceramic, and other high-end craft;
2. Comprehend overall geography, literature, and political and religious history of Japan;
3. Reconsider the construct of “Japanese” identity in various historical and cultural discourses;
4. Be enabled to think critically about the process of cultural contact (mainly with China, Korea, and the West); and
5. Develop skills in participating in scholarly arguments and writing an academic essay.

courses.course_syllabus:
The topics will include:

- history of Chinese seals;
- history of Hong Kong Seal carving;
- introduction of different seal materials; and

- authentication of Chinese seals.

courses.learning_outcomes:
After completing the course, students will be able to:

- understand fully the development and characteristics of Chinese court painting;
- evaluate objectively the role of Chinese court painting in the history of art and culture;
- understand the complex factors leading to the making of Chinese painting; and

- reflect on and analyse issues relating to art history and artistic creation.

After completing the course, students will be able to

- understand the roles, function and characteristics of Daoist art;
- analyse visual features of different art forms and their relation to Daoist beliefs and concepts;
- critically evaluate the validity of different arguments concerning a work of religious art; and

- develop skills in researching and writing critical essay on Chinese art.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

- re-develop different kind of drawing approach;
- develop individual skill and approach of mixed media;
- experimental approach and alternative making; and

- understand the imagination of content and representation of drawing

After completing the course, students will be able to:

- create time-based digital images exploring visual elements such as points, lines, forms, colors, and symbols, in a digital environment;
- capture ideal video image and sound with digital video and sound equipments for rough cuts and further editing;
- express abstract and fictional narratives through digital video and sound with a well-planned structure; and

- make good use of and have good understanding of different digital media which can be integrated in digital moving images.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

- understand fundamental knowledge of the human anatomy;
- grasp image feature and structure of figure accurately;
- improve their ability of observation, understanding and sensibility; and

- develop their skill to express themselves in figure painting.

After completing this course, students will be able to

1. acquire construction skills and knowledge in the area of ceramics;
2. practically construct forms with clay by using different methods;
3. transfer such skills and knowledge in the development of their own area of work; and

4. develop critical dialogue of ceramics in the context of visual culture and contemporary life.

After completing this course, students will be able to:

1. understand traditional and new ways of creating ceramic surfaces;
2. produce different kinds of surface on ceramic works;
3. transfer such skills and knowledge in the development of their own area of work; and

4. create critical dialogue of surface and forms in contemporary art.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

- understand the background and key issues related to certain special topics in the history of art;
- identify major scholars and their arguments on the special topics concerned;
- develop capability of evaluating the validity of different arguments; and

- write academic essays.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

1. Understand how organizations (commercial or non-profit) tackle social issues in creative ways;
2. Enhance their specialty in arts by applying their skills in an institutional and social setting;
3. Know how to deal with obstacles through problem-solving skills;
4. Learn communication skills with professionals in different fields;
5. Build network with institutions and individuals who share similar interests and beliefs;
6. Develop creative skills in implementing social engagement projects using artistic strategies.

7. Understand how public engagement with art can be analyzed and applied in different contexts, in both non-profit and commercial settings;
8. To expand their understanding of social engagement with art in an inter-disciplinary way;
9. To reflect the role of art in contemporary society and how it can be brought to the public.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

- have a full understanding of the development and characteristics of Chinese literati painting;
- objectively evaluate the role of literati painting in the history of Chinese art and culture;
- understand the literati views on and tastes of art; and

- enhance their ability to reflect on and analyse issues relating to art history and artistic creation.

After completing the course, students will be able to:

- know the general timeframe of the developments of Western art theory from Greek philosophy to the present days;
- understand the social and intellectual conditions that have produced those important texts of the history of art theory in the West;
- interpret images according to the relevant art theory; and

- rely on recent scholarship and art theory

After completing this course, student will be able to

- understand how to write an argumentative academic thesis;
- identify key issues and arguments related to the selected research topic;
- develop capability of conducting independent research; and

- complete an academic thesis.

