After completing this course, students will be able to:
- understand major traditional and modern research methodolgy in Chinese art history;
- apply different research methods to conducting art historical research;
- recognize major bibliographical works; and
- acquire skills in finding out research material with the the help of bibliographies.

After completing this course, students will be able to
- analyze the visual features as well as the philosophical, aesthetic and cultural significance of Chinese calligraphy;
- evaluate critically the validity of different arguments concerning a work of Chinese calligraphy;
- make use of different research approaches and methodologies in conducting independent research; and
- write academic papers on the art of Chinese calligraphy.

After completing this course, students will be able to
- analyze visual features of different art forms and their relation to Daoist beliefs, concepts, and scriptural traditions;
- critically evaluate the validity of different arguments concerning a work of Daoist art;
- make use of different research approaches and methodologies in conducting independent research; and
- write academic essay on religious art.

After completing this course, students will be able to
- understand thoroughly certain special areas in the history of art;
- identify key research topics, questions, scholars and their arguments related to the special areas concerned;
- critically evaluate the validity of different arguments; and
- write academic essay.

After completing this course, students will be able to
- analyze the visual features as well as the philosophical, aesthetic and cultural significance of Chinese literati painting;
- evaluate critically the validity of different arguments concerning a work of Chinese literati painting;
- make use of different research approaches and methodologies in conducting independent research; and
- write academic papers on Chinese literati painting.

After completing this course, students will be able to
- understand the development of art theory in Europe and China and how the 17th and 18th centuries were witness to profound changes in the ways painting was made as well as theorized in China and Europe;
- be able to undertake a properly conducted comparative analysis in the domain of art (the aim being not only to emphasize differences and similarities but, more importantly, to identify why these similarities and differences occurred);
- be able to use a wealth of different sources to conduct a comparative analysis of visual arts (using theoretical texts written by artists also make the use of the literature and the philosophy prevalent at the time necessary to understand the creation of a visual form of art); and
- understand how a knowledge of the past from a comparative standpoint allows for a better understanding of the cross-cultural forms of art practices so obviously a part of the cultural landscape of contemporary China.

After completing this course, students will be able to
- understand the multiple changes the concepts of art and art theory went through in Europe and North America and especially how these ideas were defined and redefined in a variety of intellectual contexts;
- understand how specific cultural and intellectual backgrounds have defined how art and art theory were understood and applied;
- be able to understand the often very complex notions addressed by contemporary artists and art theorists and how they can be situated in the long history of art theory in Europe and North America and, increasingly so in the present cross-cultural context of art practices, in the rest of the world; and
- and be able to apply the relevant notions to their own art practice if they are artists and their own research if they are art historians or art theorists/critics.

After completing the course, students will be able to:
- understand fully the development and characteristics of Chinese court painting;
- evaluate objectively the role of Chinese court painting in the history of art and culture;
- understand the complex factors leading to the making of Chinese painting; and
- reflect on and analyse issues relating to art history and artistic creation.

After completing this course, students will be able to:
- understand the general timeframe of the developments of art in Hong Kong from the late 19th century to the present days;
- reconsider the notions of ‘East’ and ‘West’ in the context of Hong Kong in light of the concepts of post-colonial studies;
- reflect on the position of Hong Kong art in connection with Chinese art in general; and
- be able to considers issues of cultural identity in art in a globalized world.

After completing this course, students will be able to
- understand how art operates in the society;
- identify elements that build the infrastructure of art in the society;
- understand an art ecology system is in fact the effective collaboration among policy maker, curator, art educator, art consultant, business sector; and
- encourage critical thinking on special issues of art related phenomena.

After completing the course, students will be able to:
- have a clear picture of the general trend of development of pre-20th century Chinese art;
- understand the great variety of Chinese art and the key characteristics of different artistic traditions;
- analyze the visual features, key concepts, artistic techniques and cultural significance of works of Chinese art;
- evaluate critically factors contributing to major changes in an artistic tradition over centuries;
- write academic essays on Chinese art.

courses.course_syllabus:
1. Topics to be covered include Chinese painting, calligraphy, religious sculpture, ceramics, lacquer, textile and print.
2. The following terms and their significance in the development of artistic traditions in China will be discussed throughout the course:
i. material and artistic skills;
ii. religious / philosophical / literary thoughts;
iii. aesthetics;
iv. tradition, innovation and transformation;
v. technological advancement;
vi. social context: prosperity and turmoil;
vii. taste and individual pursuits.

courses.learning_outcomes:
After completing this course, students will be able to:
- identify major developments of cultural theory and practice in Europe and North America after WWII;
- identify the figures, institutions, and discourses in these developments;
- situate practices of contemporary art in relation to these developments;
- formulate critical questions and arguments directly or indirectly related to practices of contemporary art as critical cultural practices; and
- propose, structure and articulate arguments and debates in writing

After completing this course, students will be able to:
- identify and critically engage with developments, appropriations and applications of theories of political economy in understanding culture in local and global conditions;
- acquire familiarity in the meanings and manifestations of “culture” and “creativity” historically and in contemporary times;
- critically formulate questions regarding the manifestations of culture and creativity in political, social, and cultural institutions;
- critically formulate questions regarding the discursive manifestations of culture and creativity;
- critically respond to recent policies and events of the “creative industries” in broader and more theoretically-informed ways; and
- propose, structure and articulate arguments and debates in writing.

After completing this course, students will be able to:
- identify and critically engage with theories of representation informed by multiple disciplines;
- articulate and debate issues regarding culture and the politics of identity;
- apply such theories and issues in everyday cultural life
- design research questions regarding the interpretation and evaluation of contemporary art in culture; and
- propose, structure and articulate arguments and debates in writing.

After completing this course, students will be able to:
- recognize the multi-disciplinary quality of “cyberculture”;
- identify key modern philosophical debates on technology;
- critically engage with such debates;
- distinguish and examine their manifestations in popular and everyday cultural forms;
- develop research and/or practice that critically respond to such issues; and
- propose, structure and articulate arguments and debates in writing.
